<statement>
<p>
Write the following symbolic statements as English sentences.
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>
  <m>(x\in \mathbb{R}) \implies (x^2\in \mathbb{R})\land (x^2\geq0)</m>.
      </p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>4\in \set{2\ell: \ell \in \mathbb{N}}</m>
    </p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>(x\in \mathbb{N}) \implies  \neg (x^2 =0). </m>
    </p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>(x\in \mathbb{Z}) \implies \big(x\in \set{2\ell: \ell \in \mathbb{Z}}\big)\lor \big(x\in \set{2k+1 : k\in \mathbb{Z}}\big)</m>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
We list a few possible English statements:
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>

	<ul>
<li>
<p>
 If <m>x</m> is a real number, then <m>x^2</m> is also a real number and <m>x^2</m> is non-negative.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 If <m>x</m> is a real number, then <m>x^2</m> is a non-negative real number.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 The square of a real number is non-negative and real.
	</p></li>
</ul>
    </p></li>
<li>
<p>

	<ul>
<li>
<p>
 <m>4</m> is an element of the set of positive, even numbers.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 We can write <m>4=2\ell</m> for some <m>\ell\in \mathbb{N}</m>.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>4</m> is a positive even number.
	</p></li>
</ul>
    </p></li>
<li>
<p>

	<ul>
<li>
<p>
 For a natural number <m>x</m>, it is not the case that <m>x^2=0</m>.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 When <m>x</m> is a natural number, <m>x^2</m> is never <m>0</m>.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 The square of a natural number is non-zero.
	</p></li>
</ul>
    </p></li>
<li>
<p>

	<ul>
<li>
<p>
  If <m>x</m> is an integer, then <m>x</m> is an even number or <m>x</m> is an odd number.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 If <m>x</m> is an integer, then it is either even or odd.
		</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 Every integer is even or odd.
	</p></li>
</ul>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</exercise>
